title: Tropical Cyclone Fina leaves Darwin residents to assess damage | ABC NEWS
description: Residents in the Top End are assessing damage from Cyclone Fina, which passed just north of Darwin as a category 3 system last night. Winds reached 140 kilometres per hour and 19,500 homes lost power. The State Emergency Service is clearing debris and reopening roads, and Darwin Airport has resumed operations. title: Severe Tropical Cyclone Fina leaves a path of destruction in her wake | ABC NEWS
description: 00:00 Severe Tropical Cyclone Fina has passed Darwin and the Tiwi Islands at category three strength, with the weather system's gale-force winds leaving a path of destruction as it continues west into the ocean. Fina was the Northern Territory's strongest cyclone to pass Darwin since the deadly Cyclone Tracy in 1974. The system was also more powerful than Cyclone Marcus, which passed Darwin as a category two in 2018. Now tracking west-south-west, Severe TC Fina is picking up strength over the Timor Sea and is expected to move over the top of Western Australia in the coming days. 02:11 ABC reporter Olivana Lathouris on trying to get a sense of when things will return to normal. 03:12 Despite the massive clean-up ahead for Darwin, the city's resilience has shone through as locals pick up the pieces ready to move on. 05:20 With power still down across parts of Darwin, Power and Water crews are working to restore as many homes as possible.  08:22 ABC meteorologist Nate Byrne on experiencing his first cyclone, and Fina's path from here. title: Tropical Cyclone Fina forecast to hit Kimberley Coast as category 2 | ABC NEWS
description: Emergency warnings have been issued for Western Australia’s north coast as Tropical Cyclone Fina roars towards the north-east Kimberley after lashing the Top End. Residents living on the coastline from the Western Australia-Northern Territory border to east of Kalumburu are bracing for more damaging winds than those which battered Darwin, as the system packs more gusts as it moves across the coast. Darwin airport has reopened, while 20,000 people remain without power and 15 schools are closed in the Northern Territory. title: Israel reportedly kills top Hezbollah official in Beirut strike | ABC NEWS
description: Israel claims its military has killed Hezbollah's chief of staff Ali Tabtabai in an air strike on the southern suburbs of the Lebanese capital, Beirut.  The Israel Defense Forces appears to have carried out the attack without prior warnings, as the United States had reportedly not been notified. Meanwhile, Israeli strikes in Gaza have killed dozens and injured many more in response to what Israeli authorities claim were ceasefire breaches by Hamas.  The Palestinian health authority says women and children were among the casualties. title: Adam Spencer on the CSIRO job cuts | ABC News Daily podcast
description: Our peak scientific body, the CSIRO, has made extraordinary discoveries and invented everyday wonders like Aerogard, plastic banknotes and WiFi.    But once again the CSIRO is axing jobs, saying the cost of doing science has outpaced its funding and it needs to refocus on big issues.    Today, Adam Spencer, ambassador for mathematics and science at Sydney University on what happens when science is underfunded.    Featured:    Adam Spencer, science communicator and University of Sydney’s mathematics and science ambassador

title: Parts of NSW set to swelter under heatwave conditions | ABC NEWS
description: Parts of coastal and central NSW could see temperatures in the high 30s to mid 40s. The Northern Tablelands and Mid North Coast will be hit hardest, with temperatures to stick around in the high 20s overnight. The BOM has issued heatwave warnings for the Northern Rivers, Mid North Coast, Northern Tablelands and Upper Western region. title: Rents surge in regional Australia and steady in cities, report shows | ABC NEWS
description: The rental crisis in regional Australia has deteriorated while rental crisis in major cities has stabilised for now, according to a new rental affordability report.  The 11th annual Rental Affordability Index by SGS Economics and Planning shows a dire picture for regional areas such as Victoria’s Wodonga, Woodend and Waradyte. title: White House confirms department once led by Elon Musk to cut spending is gone | ABC NEWS
description: The White House has confirmed the Department of Government Efficiency (DOGE) to cut spending no longer exists. It was set up by Donald Trump and headed by billionaire Elon Musk to slash billions of dollars from the US government. Since Mr Musk left his role, it has quietly faded into the background.
